The XPS spectra are used to investigate the surface chemical composition of PANI/BiOBr/ZnFe2O4 composite and the results are presented in Fig. 2
                        (a)–(f). Fig. 2a displays two strong peaks of Bi 4f5/2 and Bi 4f7/2 at 164.32 eV and 159.02 eV, which correspond to Bi3+ in the PANI/BiOBr/ZnFe2O4 composite [39]. It is noteworthy that the binding energy of Bi 4f in PANI/BiOBr/ZnFe2O4 composite exhibits a slightly shift compared with pure BiOBr, indicating that there is an interfacial interaction between PANI, BiOBr and ZnFe2O4 
                        [17,40]. The similar shifts are observed in the Br 3d spectra as shown in Fig. 2b, the peaks at 69.17 eV and 68.17 eV are attributed to the binding energy of Br 3d3/2 and Br 3d5/2, respectively. The binding energies of oxygen elements can be analyzed from Fig. 2c. The characteristic peaks at 529.77 eV, 531.27 eV and 532.87 eV belong to lattice oxygen species bound of O2−, Fe-O and Bi-O [41], respectively. It can be inferred that there are a number of oxygen species adsorbed on the surface of the PANI/BiOBr/ZnFe2O4 composite, which also indicates that the oxygen element exists in the form of O2− and enhanced the activity of the catalyst. The characteristic peaks with binding energies of 724.72 eV and 710.78 eV belong to Fe 2p1/2 and Fe 2p3/2 
                        [42] (Fig. 2d), respectively, which confirms that Fe element in the composite exists in the state of Fe3+. The binding energy of zinc element as presented in Fig. 2e, the characteristic peaks appear at 1055.05 eV and 1021.67 eV are attributed to Zn 2p1/2 and Zn 2p3/2, which indicates that Zn element exists as Zn2+ in PANI/BiOBr/ZnFe2O4 composite [34]. As shown in Fig. 2f, the N 1 s spectrum of PANI/BiOBr/ZnFe2O4 can be divided into four peaks, which are located in 398.28 eV, 399.62 eV, 400.87 eV and 405.48 eV. The binding energies are assigned to the neutral imine nitrogen atom (NH), neutral amine (MNH), positively charged nitrogen (

                        ) and protonated imine (

                        ) [18], respectively. Particularly, the existence of M-NH- further proves that a chemical interaction between π-conjugated PANI, BiOBr and ZnFe2O4 is formed.

The degradation of RhB aqueous solution (20 mg/L) over the catalysts under visible-light exposure at room temperature exhibited in Fig. 6
                           a. PANI shows the highest adsorption capacity for RhB dyes after stirring in dark for 30 min. This is attribute to PANI containing sulfosalicylic acid has a strong adsorption capacity for positively charged RhB dyes. Meanwhile, ZnFe2O4 also exhibits a good adsorption properties for RhB dyes due to its large specific surface area and positive charge on the surface. Additionally, the PANI/BiOBr/ZnFe2O4 ternary composite displays a much better adsorption ability for RhB dye after the introduction of PANI and ZnFe2O4. After illumination for 30 min, there is no doubt the PANI/BiOBr/ZnFe2O4 composite exhibits an obviously enhanced photocatalytic degradation efficiency with respect to pure BiOBr, BiOBr/ZnFe2O4 and BiOBr/PANI. Furthermore, the optimal addition of PANI in PANI/BiOBr/ZnFe2O4 composite was determined by a series of photocatalytic experiments (Fig. 6b). Specifically, 7% PANI/BiOBr/ZnFe2O4 shows the best degradation performance for RhB, and the degradation rate is as high as 99.26% in the presence of 7% PANI/BiOBr/ZnFe2O4 composite. The experimental results show that the photocatalytic efficiency decreases when the PANI content increases from 7 wt% to 9 wt%. The decline can be attributed to the following two aspects. On the one hand, the excessive PANI may shield the incident visible-light, which could hinders the generation of electron carriers in BiOBr. On the other hand, loading excessive PANI will lead to the formation of new photo-generated carrier recombination centers, thus, resulting in rapidly charge recombination. Fig. 6c shows the change of absorption spectrum of RhB degraded by 7% PANI/BiOBr/ZnFe2O4 composite. The intensity of the characteristic peak at 554 nm decreases significantly with the increase of irradiation time, and the characteristic peak displays a slightly blue-shifted, which ascribed to the de-ethylation and conjugate structure damage of RhB. The corresponding first-order kinetic equation expressed as -ln(Ct/C0
                           ) = kt was fitted to have a better understanding of the degradation rate, where Ct and C0 are MB concentrations at t time and initial time respectively, and k represents reaction rate constant (min−1). As shown in Fig. 6d, the 7% PANI/BiOBr/ZnFe2O4 composite exhibits the highest degradation rate for RhB (k = 0.14815 min−1), which is 6.22, 1.76 and 2.97 times higher than that of BiOBr, BiOBr/ZnFe2O4 and BiOBr/PANI, respectively. It indicates the interaction in the PANI/BiOBr/ZnFe2O4 composite leads to the enhancement of photocatalytic performance.

Moreover, the photocatalytic reduction of nitrobenzene (NB) over 7% PANI/BiOBr/ZnFe2O4 composite (Fig. 7
                           a and 7b) was also investigated under visible light irradiation. Fig. 7a shows that the conversion of NB over the composite can reach 87.1% after irradiation for 60 min. Moreover, the intensity change of characteristic peak (about 267 nm) was recorded by UV spectroscopy in the presence of PANI/BiOBr/ZnFe2O4 composite (inset of Fig. 7a), which decreased significantly after irradiation for 60 min. The reduction process of NB can also be accepted as a pseudo-first order reaction, and Fig. 7b shows the linear relationship of -ln (Ct/C0
                           ) vs reaction time. It is can be seen that the apparent kinetic rate constant (k) value of PANI/BiOBr/ZnFe2O4 composite is 0.02884 min−1. In addition, the mineralization efficiency of pollutants is very important for its degradation evaluation. Fig. 7c shows that the mineralization rate of RhB of PANI/BiOBr/ZnFe2O4 is 77.92% after visible light irradiation for 30 min. The mineralization rate of NB is 50.79% after irradiation for 30 min, and the mineralization rate increases with the increase of time. The results also show that PANI/BiOBr/ZnFe2O4 composite exhibits the excellent performance for the degradation of RhB and NB. HPLC analysis was carried out to further confirm the photocatalytic reduction product of NB over PANI/BiOBr/ZnFe2O4 composite. As exhibited in Fig. 7e, the chromatographic peak at approximately 8.3 min belongs to NB, which decreases significantly after irradiation for 60 min, indicating that NB was reduced. At the same time, a new chromatograph peak appeared at approximately 4.0 min. Comparison of the standard retention time and chromatographic peak shape of NB and AN, confirming that NB was reduced to AN with the reduction of NO2 group to NH2 group via photocatalytic. The reduction product AN with lower toxicity is an important organic intermediate, which can be widely used in the production of dyes, pigments, pesticides and pharmaceuticals. Therefore, the study of NB reduction to AN has a great reference value for environmental protection and industrial production.
